UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 2376
1 A JOINT RESOLUTION directing the Kentucky Office of Homeland Security to
2 conduct investigations measuring the Commonwealth's capabilities and vulnerabilities
3 during a potential conflict in the Indo-Pacific and European regions.
4 WHEREAS, recent events have created a heightened risk of conflict that would
5 endanger the vital interests and national security of the United States of America; and
6 WHEREAS, it is the duty of the government of the Commonwealth to take all
7 reasonable steps to prepare for potential conflicts that may disrupt or harm Kentucky
8 residents, businesses, and governments or otherwise affect Kentucky interests; and
9 WHEREAS, Kentucky shall always support the efforts of the government of the
10 United States of America to promote and maintain prosperity, peace, and security for
11 America and her allies; and
12 WHEREAS, the General Assembly shall exercise foresight and take all reasonable
13 steps to assess the preparedness of the Commonwealth for a potential regional or global
14 conflict, which could involve attacks upon the United States and her allies, and which
15 could cause disruption or the severing of economic business relationships and supply
16 chains between and among Kentucky and businesses abroad;
17 NOW, THEREFORE,
18 Be it resolved by the General Assembly of the Commonwealth of Kentucky:
19 Section 1. (1) The Kentucky Office of Homeland Security shall conduct
20 tabletop exercises to assess how conflicts in the Indo-Pacific and European regions would
21 affect Kentucky. These exercises shall explore scenarios that would focus on aggression
22 upon the United States Armed Forces in each of those regions and involve intentional or
23 incidental damage to Kentucky supply chains, critical infrastructure, military
24 installations, and other assets. The Kentucky Office of Homeland Security shall report
25 findings to the Legislative Research Commission and the Governor within 180 days
26 following the effective date of this Resolution detailing how potential conflicts in those
27 regions would impact the Commonwealth.
