UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 2376
1 (2) The Kentucky Office of Homeland Security, in conjunction with the Finance
2 and Administration Cabinet, shall evaluate critical procurements purchased or supplied
3 through state supply chains that would be disrupted in the event of conflicts in the Indo-
4 Pacific and European regions. The Kentucky Office of Homeland Security shall submit
5 findings to the Legislative Research Commission and the Governor within 180 days
6 following the effective date of this Resolution. These findings shall, at a minimum:
7 (a) Identify all critical state procurements produced in or by a foreign country in
8 the Indo-Pacific or European regions, a state-owned enterprise of a foreign country in the
9 Indo-Pacific or European regions, a company domiciled within a foreign country in the
10 Indo-Pacific or European regions, or a company owned by a company domiciled in a
11 foreign country in the Indo-Pacific or European regions, or substantially sourced from the
12 same;
13 (b) Identify all state critical procurements manufactured in countries, or by
14 companies, at risk of disruption in the event of a conflict in the Indo-Pacific or European
15 regions;
16 (c) Identify all state critical procurements sourced from any country or company
17 that utilizes supply chains or business or manufacturing processes in the Indo-Pacific or
18 European regions that would be at risk of disruption in the event of such conflicts; and
19 (d) Recommend alternative sourcing strategies, if available; highlight the
20 difficulty in identifying potential alternative sourcing, if necessary; and specify the level
21 of risk to the Commonwealth associated with such a disruption in supply chain sourcing
22 for each procurement that would be threatened in the event of a conflict in the Indo-
23 Pacific or European regions.
24 (3) The Kentucky Office of Homeland Security, in conjunction with the
25 Commission on Military Affairs and the Public Service Commission, shall investigate
26 potential threats to critical Kentucky infrastructure and Kentucky military installations in
27 the event of conflicts in the Indo-Pacific and European regions. The Kentucky Office of
