UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 2376
1 Homeland Security shall produce initial findings to the Legislative Research Commission
2 and the Governor within 180 days following the effective date of this Resolution and a
3 final analysis with recommendations within one year following the effective date of this
4 Resolution. The findings shall, at a minimum:
5 (a) Identify all critical infrastructure, military installations, and other assets
6 within Kentucky that could reasonably be targeted in malicious actions by outside nations
7 in the event of a conflict in the Indo-Pacific or European regions, which could result in a
8 significant negative impact on the public health, safety, economic security, or physical
9 security of the Commonwealth and its citizens;
10 (b) Identify risks posed to each infrastructure system, military installation, or
11 other asset in the event of a conflict in the Indo-Pacific or European regions; and
12 (c) Recommend strategies to prevent and protect against threats posed to
13 Kentucky critical infrastructure, military installations, and other assets in the event of a
14 potential conflict in the Indo-Pacific or European regions, and develop strategies to
15 minimize threats in the event that such attacks succeed in damaging Kentucky critical
16 infrastructure or military installations.
17 (4) Any research, data, reports, findings, and other information produced pursuant
18 to this Resolution shall be classified as confidential and shall not be subject to release
19 under KRS 61.870 to 61.884 or KRS 7.119, and shall be compiled within and kept
20 confidential by the Office of the Governor and the Legislative Research Commission.
21 (5) The Kentucky Office of Homeland Security shall provide a report within one
22 year following the effective date of this Resolution, with narrative and summary findings
23 from the investigations set out in this Resolution for the purposes of educating Kentucky
24 residents. The report may include policy recommendations for consideration by state and
25 local governments and recommendations to improve the resilience of Kentucky's
26 economy and government. The report shall not contain any information which would
27 pose a risk to the security of the Commonwealth.
